  "prompt": "How did you get into IIM?",
  "response": "Getting into the Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs) typically involves a few key steps:\n\n1. **Common Admission Test (CAT):** The first and foremost step is to appear for the Common Admission Test (CAT), which is a highly competitive exam conducted annually. It tests candidates on quantitative ability, verbal ability, reading comprehension, data interpretation, and logical reasoning.\n\n2. **CAT Score:** Based on your performance in CAT, you receive a percentile score. IIMs have varying cut-offs, but generally, a high percentile (usually above 90-95) is required to be considered for the next stage.\n\n3. **Application:** After the CAT results are announced, you need to apply to the IIMs you are interested in. This involves filling out an application form where you provide details of your academic qualifications, work experience, and other relevant information.\n\n4. **Shortlisting:** IIMs shortlist candidates based on their CAT scores, academic records, work experience, and other criteria. Each IIM has its own criteria and weightage system.\n\n5. **Written Ability Test (WAT) and Personal Interview (PI):** If shortlisted, you will be called for the Written Ability Test (WAT) and Personal Interview (PI). Some IIMs also include Group Discussions (GD) as part of their selection process. These are crucial stages where candidates are evaluated on their communication skills, knowledge, and overall personality.\n\n6. **Final Selection:** Based on your performance in CAT, WAT, PI, GD (if applicable), and your overall profile, IIMs make their final selections. Each IIM has its own criteria and weightage for final selection.\n\n7. **Offer of Admission:** If you are selected, you will receive an offer of admission from the respective IIM(s). You need to accept the offer and complete the requisite formalities to secure your seat.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that preparation for CAT and the subsequent stages requires dedication, consistent effort, and strategic planning. Many candidates also take coaching or join preparatory courses to enhance their chances.",
